note.para:
svg_color has a constructor for svg_color_constant, so you can use a svg_color_constant in place of a svg_color and it will be implicitly converted. However, there is not currently an svg_color::operator=(svg_color_constant) overload, so
svg_color my_color = red;
does not work.

row.entry:
Pushes a path_element to the back of the tree and returns a reference to it. This allows you to do the following:
path_element& my_path = image.path();
my_path.M(3, 3).l(150, 150);
I'm open to suggestions for how to improve this process.

Set the background color
            for the legend as col,
            an RGB color

A class or that contains
              a conversion function. You will not have to worry about this, unless
              you are trying to accomplish stuff like plotting a vector of humans.
              For example: 

class my_functor
{
	typdef double result_type;

	double operator()(const human& _hum)
	{
		return (double)(_hum.age());
	}
}

// snip

plot(my_plot, my_data, "Lions", _functor = my_functor());

Set the background color
            for the legend as col,
            an RGB color

A class or that contains
              a conversion function. You will not have to worry about this, unless
              you are trying to accomplish stuff like plotting a vector of humans.
              For example: 

class my_functor
{
	typdef pair<double, double> result_type;
	static double i = 0;

	pair<double, double> operator()(const human& _hum)
	{
		i+=1.;
		return pair<double, double>(i, _hum.age());
	}
}

// snip

plot(my_plot, my_data, "Lions", _x_functor = my_functor());
